./.title: Introduction
./.body:
Introduction
This gitbook explains how to use DeepLabCut in Windows, together with Google Colaboratory. 
DeepLabCut can estimate and label bodybart positions based on deep-learning of a training dataset.
The version of DeepLabCut is 2.2rc3
Referenced websites (in Japanese)

DeepLabCutをWindows+google colaboratoryで使ってみた - Qiita
深層学習で動物の身体をトラッキングするdeeplabcutをgoogle colaboratoryで走らせる - Qiita
DeepLabCutのインストールについての備忘録 - Hatena Blog

markdown/01.html.title: 1. SETTING UP A VIRTUAL ENVIRONMENT
markdown/01.html.body:
1. SETTING UP A VIRTUAL ENVIRONMENT
1.1 Launch 'Anaconda Prompt' (command prompt) as an administrator
'Anaconda Prompt' can be found 
Start -> Anaconda3 (64-bit) -> Annaconda Prompt
Right-click 'Annaconda Prompt' and select 'More'-> 'Run as administrator'.
The administrator access is critical for DeepLabCut to output files 
1.2 Set up a virtual environment
Run the following line in the Annaconda Prompt
conda activate deeplabcut

1.3 change a working directory
The default current directory should be C:\Windows\system32, but making new files there would be a mess.
Therefore, it is highly recommended to prepare a separate direcotry, and change (cd command) to there as a working directory. 
For expamle, if you want to change to a folder named DeepLabCut in the Documents folder of {UserName}'s, run the following line.
cd C:\Users\UserName\Documents\DeepLabCut

At the moment, the directory in the newtork drive S cannot be selected for unknown reasons.
This gitbook will describe the following steps, assuming you have a virtual environment at

C drive
Users
UserName
Documents
DeepLabCut









1.4 Copy video files to the working directory
The copying is not mandatory, but makes the following steps easy to process. 
This gitbook assumes that the video files are placed in the working directory.

markdown/02.html.title: 2. CREATION OF A PROJECT
markdown/02.html.body:
2. CREATION OF A PROJECT
All of the steps in this chapter is in the Python Command Prompt
2.1 Start Python
Run the fllowing code
python

2.2 load deeplabcut libraries
Run the fllowing code. It may take time.
import deeplabcut

2.3 Create a project
Run the following code, after modifying 'task_name', 'researcher_name', 'video_path_list'
This code will creates, within your working direcotry, a project folder named task-researcher-yyyy-mm-dd.
Warning : function deeplabcut.create_new_project() can get input copy_videos as False or True.
This gitbook chooses False, which does not copy the video, but instead create a link file. 
The link file requires an additional step later to upload a video to Google Colab.
Instead of False, you could choose True for input copy_videos. This choice will copy a video in the working directory. 
# lines to edit ---
# name of the task
task_name = 'task'

# name of one who does labeling
researcher_name = 'researcher'

# paths to vidoe files
video_path_list = [ 'C:\\*****\\video1.avi', 'C:\\*****\\video2.avi' ] # when you have two videos
#video_path_list = [ 'video1.avi' ] # when one video. The format still needs to be [];

# lines not to edit ---
# creation of a project
deeplabcut.create_new_project( task_name , researcher_name, video_path_list, copy_videos = True )

# save paths (for later)
import os; import datetime;
todays_date = datetime.datetime.now().strftime('%Y-%m-%d')
path_project = os.getcwd() + f'\\{task_name}-{researcher_name}-{todays_date}'
path_config = path_project + "\\config.yaml"

The directory structure of this specific example should be the following. 

C drive
Users
UserName
Documents
DeepLabCut
task-researcher-yyyy-mm-dd
config.yaml
dlc-models
labeled-data
training-datasets
videos

markdown/03.html.title: 3. EDITS of config.yaml
markdown/03.html.body:
3. EDITS of config.yaml
 In this chapter, the work steps are with an editor application (such as Notepad). Do not touch the Python Command Prompt which we justed work with 
3.1 open config.yaml
The newly created project folder task-researcher-yyyy-mm-dd should have config.yaml inside.
config.yaml will be edited. Editor applications can be any, including Vscode or Notepad.

task-researcher-yyyy-mm-dd
config.yaml
dlc-models
labeled-data
training-datasets
videos



3.2 edit config.yaml
You need to edit bodyparts and numframes2pick
# --- omitted ---
bodyparts: # lines to specify
- bodypart1
- bodypart2
- bodypart3
- objectA
start: 0
stop: 1
numframes2pick: 50 # line to specify

# --- omitted ----


what is 'bodyparts'?
  bodyparts defines everything that needs to be tracked. They can include not only body parts, but also bars, a spout, etc.
  There is no limit how many bodyparts you want to create. 
  to define an item to track, 

name to track
For example, if we plan to track a lowerjaw and a spout, then the code should be like the following. 
```yaml
bodyparts:

lowerjaw
spout
```
It is recommended that bodyparts have some spatial order in the video. For instance the 1st bodyparts is from the top, and the last from the bottom. 



what is numframes2pick?
  numframes2pick specifies a number of frames to label as a training dataset. Defualt number is 20.
  The larger the numframes2pick is, the better model the network can develop. 
  In particular, larger numframes2picktracking is necessary for a body part which rarely shows up (e.g., tongue). 
  On the other hand, the larger numframes2picktracking means more effort for labeling.
  Here we will proceed with the default number, 20.
  numframes2pick: 20



3.3 overwrite 'config.yaml'
After all the edits are done, save (overwrite) config.yaml. You can close the editor application here.

markdown/04.html.title: 4. EXTRACTING FRAMES AND LABELING
markdown/04.html.body:
4. EXTRACTING FRAMES AND LABELING
This chapter uses Command Prompt
Based on the modified information in 'config.yaml', we will extract frames and label points as a trainer dataset. 
4.1 extract frames
In the previous step, config.yaml set numframes2pick. 
Here, that amount of frames are used for a training dataset.
The training dataset needs to be manually labeled, using function deeplabcut.extract_frames().
See details here.
Simplified explanation for this function follows below.
In this example, We will use kmeans clustering to select frames for training
Run the following code. 
deeplabcut.extract_frames(path_config, 'automatic', 'kmeans')

For each video, you are asked '「Do you want to extract (perhaps additional) frames for vidoe: ###.avi?」'. 
If you prefer to use automatic mode for one video and manual mode for the others, choose yes, no accordingly. 

If you got lost which directory you are now in, run the following code. 
import os
os.getcwd()

4.2 Start a DeepLabCut GUI to label frames of the training dataset
Call the function deeplabcut.label_frames(path_config).
deeplabcut.label_frames(path_config)

Run this code, then the GUI of DeepLabCut should be opened

markdown/04_add.html.title: what function extract_frames() does
markdown/04_add.html.body:
what function extract_frames() does
We will explain how
deeplabcut.extract_frames(config,
    mode="automatic",
    algo="kmeans",
    cluster_step=1,
    cluster_color=False)
works. Here we use 5 arguments, but it can be more. See details here.

The 1st argument config
  config needs to be a path of config.yaml



The 2nd argument  mode 
  mode can be either"automatic" or "manual"

"automatic" is to select frames based on the following algorithm algo.
"manual" is to specify frames manually




The 3rd argument  algo 
  algo can be either"kmeans"or"uniform". algo will be active only whenmode is set as"automatic"

"kmeans"　first groups frames into clusters, then select frames from the clusters
"uniform" select frames at a certain interval.




The 4th argument  cluster_step

option to reduce the video frames. 1 will use all the vidoe frames, and 10 will use 1th, 11th, 21th, 31th, ... frames. , ...
  computation of kmeans is demanding, but the demand can be reduced by cluster_step （ref : https://note.com/sakulab/n/n539e6b934667 ）

Default is 1.



The 5th argument  cluster_color
  Defualt is False. Set as False, each frame will be processed as grayscale vector (no color info).
As True, color channels will be kept but the computation will get complicated.

markdown/05.html.title: 5. LABELING THE TRAINING DATASET
markdown/05.html.body:
5. LABELING THE TRAINING DATASET
This chapter uses DeepLabCut's GUI. Leave the Anaconda Prompt as it is 
5.1 Open
ClickLoad frames, then list of labeled-data folder will be shown.
Choose a folder (not a file) whose name is the same with the video to be analyzed, and then click Open at the bottom right. 
Then, a new window pops up for labeling points. 
5.2 Labeling
For every frame using the labeling window, 

right click to create a new marker, left click to move the marker'. 
Individual bodyparts need a maker. Once a marker is created for one bodypart, you need to move on to the next bodypart. The marker you are creating or moving can be selected on the Select a bodypart to label.

If some bodyparts cannot be found in a specific frame, skip that frame for the bodyparts.

A marker can be removed by left-clicking it and then pressing the delete key

Once you labels markers for all bodyparts, move on to the next frame by clickng Next.


Once you complete all frames, do not forget to click Save.
Then, the window can be closed by clicking x. Quit will move on to a next video if any.
explanation of each button

Next and Previous 
  change the frame to be shown.

Zoom  By pressing Zoom, you can select a square region to be zoomed in. Home button will make the zoom back to 1.

Pan  Pan moves a field ov view. 

Home  Make the view back to the default (after view is changed by Zoom or Pan buttons)

Lock 
  Even when you move to a different frame, a field of view is locked.

markdown/06.html.title: 6. RE-LABELING AND CONFIRMATION OF LABELLED FRAMES
markdown/06.html.body:
6. RE-LABELING AND CONFIRMATION OF LABELLED FRAMES
This chaper describes steps with Anaconda Prompt. The steps in this chapter can be skipped
6.0 Re-label markers
New! : 
After automatic labeling, if you find some markers seldom labeled, you can select frames manually as described below. 
deeplabcut.extract_frames(path_config, 'manual')

How to select frames manually : Selection is based on a GUI, which is similar to labeling steps.

First, click Load Video, then select a video file insdie the 'videos' folder.
Next, you are asked "Do you Want to Crop the frames?". In most cases, "No" should be fine, but if you select "Yes", define a square with your cursor, and click Set.
Then, select frames by pressing Grab Frames. It is sometimes not obvious but one click is sufficient to select the frame. 
If you move on to the next frame one by one, press → ←. If you use a scroll bar, you can jump to specific frames.
20-30 frames are sufficient for one bodypart. 
Once you finish the selection, close the window. 

Once the frames are selected, mark labels as before. 
Here you need to go through the newly selected frames together with previously used ones. These frames are in time sequence, so unlabeled and already labeled frames are mixed. So all the frames need to be checked.  
deeplabcut.label_frames(path_config)

6.1 Create frames to confirm labeling
The following code creates the frames for confirmation. 
path_config is the same with one used in function label_frames().
deeplabcut.check_labels(path_config)

CAUTION: occassionally this funciton cannot be run. You can proceed without the confirmation of frames. 

If you are unsure which directory you are now at, run the following code. 
import os
os.getcwd()

6.2 Inspect
The above code creates frames in the folder, labeled-data, insdie the folder, 'task-researcher-yyyy-mm-dd'.
6.3 Exit
click x, and then close Anamconda Prompt.

markdown/07.html.title: 7. Google Colaboratory
markdown/07.html.body:
7. Google Colaboratory
This chapter uses Google Drive and Google Colab
7.1 Upload the folder just created to the Google Drive directory
The folder 'task-researcher-yyyy-mm-dd' needs to be uploaded to Google Drive directory (e.g. My Drive > DeepLabCut >).
7.2 Uplaod a Notebook to the Google Drive directory
Download notebook from here
and upload it to the Google Drive directory of task-researcher-yyyy-mm-dd
This Google Drive directory needs to have a config.yaml.
Downloading can be done as File -> Download -> as .ipynb
7.3 Upload video files
In the Google Drive direcotory 'task-researcher-yyyy-mm-dd' has a folder 'videos'. Inside the folder, there is a avi file, but this is just a link file not an actual one.
Replace the link file with an actual video file. Uploading the actual file to Google Drive can take time, but you can proceed without waiting for the uploading to be completed. 
7.4 Open the Notebook with Google Colabo
The notebook just uploaded needs to be opend with Google Colabo. Right click and select Open with -> Google Colaboratory
From here, we will run codes in the notebook, so the relevant explanations are written there.

markdown/08.html.title: 8. IMPROVEMENT OF THE TRAINING RESULTS
markdown/08.html.body:
8. IMPROVEMENT OF THE TRAINING RESULTS
This chapter uses Google Drive, Google Colabo, Anaconda Prompt
To improve the results, you need to select specific frames which perform poorly, and then re-label the training set to re-train the netwrok. 
8.1 Download a project folder from the Google Drive
Download a project folder which Google Calb just made. 
Then put the folder in your local directory that you will run Anaconda Prompt (wich cd command)
8.2 Run Anaconda Prompt as an administrator, and create a virtual environment.
Do the same steps with 1. SETTING UP A VIRTUAL ENVIRONMENT and * 2. CREATION OF A PROJECT 2.2
8.3 Select frames which are expected to perform poorly
First, select frames that result in poor performance, using function deeplabcut.extract_outlier_frames().
There are four ways to judge which frames makes the performnace poor. 
The four approaches can be chosen as theoutlieralgorithmargument of functiondeeplabcut.extract_outlier_frames().
The default approach isoutlieralgorithm = 'jump'`
The first is to choose frames based on their low likelihood for each labeled bodypart. 
outlieralgorithm = 'uncertain'

the threshold for the likelifood can be set as the argument p_bound. The default value is p_bound = 0.01.

The second is based the acceptable range which moving-average fitting can predict in the xy coordinate for each labeled bodypart.
outlieralgorithm = 'Fitting'

the accepatable range can be set as the argument epsilon. The default is epsilon = 20.

The third is based on the transient jump in the xy coordinate for each labeled bodypart. 
outlieralgorithm = 'jump'

the extent of jump is set as the argument epsilon. The defualt is epsilon = 20.

The last is maunal. 
`outlieralgorithm = 'manual' 
For explanations in details, see here
import os

# info to be edited
path_project = os.getcwd() + "\\task-researcher-yyyy-mm-dd" # please edit here

video_name_list = [ '*****.avi', '*****.avi'] # please edit video file names***** Not necessary to include path

# Don't edit
path_config = path_project + '\\config.yaml'
video_path_list = list(map(lambda x: path_project+"\\videos\\"+x, video_name_list))

# option selection
deeplabcut.extract_outlier_frames(path_config, video_path_list, outlieralgorithm = 'jump') # 'jump' is the default

Enter yes for videos that needs additional training. It can take a while. 
8.4 Change the position of labelled markers.
function deeplabcut.refine_labels() readjust the position of labelled markers for exracted frames. 
deeplabcut.refine_labels(path_config)

A GUI will be started. This time, select a h5 file instead of a folder (different from deeplabcut.label_frames). 
go to a folder task-researcher-yyyy-mm-dd, select machinelabels-iter0.h5, and then click Open
You will be asked about a threshold for the likelihood. 
Try 0.40 (defualt). 
Then, for each extracted frames (with low likeliehoo), you can confirm the marker position. 
In some frames, you need to remove the makers, by pressing a mouse wheel (different from deeplabcut.label_frames).
Complete all frames. 
8.5 Mearge the newly corrected data as a trained set.
Function deeplabcut.merge_datasets() can merge the corrected data.

deeplabcut.merge_datasets(path_config)

Now the new training is ready to be run. 
8.6 When you want to add new videos, as new training sets
New videos can be added by functiondeeplabcut.add_new_videos()
video_path_list_add = [ 'C:\\*****\\*****.avi' ] # full path

deeplabcut.add_new_videos(path_config, video_path_list_add, copy_videos = True)

Go back to the steps in 4. EXTRACTING FRAMES AND LABELING
deeplabcut.extract_frames(path_config, 'automatic', 'kmeans')

import os
os.getcwd()

deeplabcut.label_frames(path_config)

8.7 Upload the project to the Google Drive directory
Upload the project folder 'task-researcher-yyyy-mm-dd' to the Google Drive
Go back to the steps in 7. Google Colaboratory
